1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,860
This is Mano Vaarta. It opens like a calm private
check-in, not a rigid form.

2
00:00:06,580 --> 00:00:16,250
Users can switch between English, Hindi, and Hinglish
right away, because real conversations rarely stay inside
one perfectly clean language.

3
00:00:15,970 --> 00:00:25,330
Starting a session takes one tap. After that, the layout
stays simple. Conversation on the left. Quiet guidance on
the right.

4
00:00:25,050 --> 00:00:35,630
Now I can type naturally. I do not have to translate my
feelings into questionnaire language. I can just say that
sleep keeps breaking and focus is getting worse.

5
00:00:35,350 --> 00:00:42,760
The reply does not rush into a score. It reflects what it
heard, and then asks the next useful follow-up.

6
00:00:42,480 --> 00:00:52,920
At the same time, the product keeps a plain-language
summary, explains why the next question matters, and keeps
comfort and safety visible in the background.

7
00:00:52,640 --> 00:01:04,350
If typing feels tiring, voice replies and continuous voice
mode can take over. The goal is a smoother back and forth,
closer to a guided conversation than a form.

8
00:01:04,070 --> 00:01:14,440
What matters is that the product feels calmer, more
conversational, and easier to return to. That is the idea
behind Mano Vaarta.
